('computer-science:2-2-3e-subprograms-and-random-numbers:tips:c72d0815', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3e-subprograms-and-random-numbers', '2.2.3e Sub Programs and Random Numbers', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Local vs global — always check WHERE it''s declared", "reading": "<p>Scope questions (local or global?) are decided entirely by <strong>where a variable is first declared</strong> — nothing else matters:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Declared <strong>inside</strong> a function or procedure (including as a parameter)? → <strong>local</strong>.</li>\n<li>Declared <strong>outside</strong> every sub program? → <strong>global</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Don''t be tricked by a global variable being <strong>used</strong> inside a sub program — using it there doesn''t make it local. Only where it is <strong>declared</strong> decides its scope.</p>", "question": "A variable is declared inside a procedure, but the main program also happens to reference that same variable''s name elsewhere by mistake. What decides whether the variable is local or global?", "options": ["Only where the variable was first declared, not where it is later used or referenced", "Whichever part of the program uses the variable most often decides its scope", "The variable becomes global automatically the moment it is used outside its own sub program", "Scope is decided by the variable''s data type, not by where it happens to be declared"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Scope is fixed by WHERE a variable is declared — inside a sub program means local, outside every sub program means global."}'::jsonb),
